  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects of AML regulations typically include:\n\n1. Mandatory reporting of suspicious financial transactions\n2. Customer identification and verification requirements\n3. Record-keeping rules\n4. Requirements for financial institutions to have internal compliance programs\n5. Penalties for non-compliance\n\nMajor examples include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States\n- European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) international standards\n- Similar regulations in countries like Canada, Australia, and the UK\n\nThese regulations apply to banks, financial institutions, cryptocurrency exchanges, and other entities that handle financial transactions.",
